/* ---- BLOG DATA ---- */
var BLOG=[{d:"Apr 5, 2026",t:"The Invisible Handoff",tg:"Design",b:"I have been thinking about what happens between the moment someone downloads Superhuman and the moment they feel faster than Gmail. That gap is where most churn lives. The best activation is invisible. It does not feel like onboarding. It feels like the product is just... working for you from the start.",sec:[{h:"Key Thought",items:["Activation should feel like the product, not a tutorial","Every tooltip is a design failure worth examining","The goal is muscle memory, not comprehension"]}]},{d:"Apr 1, 2026",t:"Building HyperFlow",tg:"Process",b:"I have started building HyperFlow as a speculative activation layer for Superhuman. The process has been deeply rewarding. Using AI tools to accelerate research and prototyping while keeping all design decisions human-led feels like the right balance for this kind of work.",sec:[{h:"Process Notes",items:["20/60/20 approach: human-led framing, AI-accelerated building, human-led polish","Every screen grounded in real activation patterns from competitive analysis","AI supplements the creative process but never replaces design judgment"]}]},{d:"Mar 28, 2026",t:"Why Email Still Matters",tg:"Industry",b:"In a world of Slack threads and Notion docs, email remains the universal inbox. Superhuman understood this early. The opportunity is not replacing email but making it feel like a superpower. When I watch power users triage 200 messages in under 15 minutes, I see what great design makes possible.",sec:[{h:"Observation",items:["Email is the last truly universal communication protocol","Speed is a feeling, not just a metric","The keyboard-first paradigm rewards investment"]}]},{d:"Mar 22, 2026",t:"Designing for Habit Formation",tg:"Research",b:"I spent time studying BJ Fogg's behavior model and how it applies to productivity tools. The insight that changed my thinking: motivation is unreliable, but making the desired behavior tiny and easy is something design can always do. That is what activation should optimize for.",sec:[{h:"Framework",items:["Trigger + Ability + Motivation = Behavior","Design for the smallest possible successful action","Streaks work because they shift identity, not just behavior"]}]},{d:"Mar 15, 2026",t:"Mobile Email is Broken",tg:"Design",b:"Most email clients treat mobile as a read-only surface. You can scan, maybe archive, but real work waits for desktop. Superhuman's mobile app is better than most, but there is still a gap between desktop power users and mobile triage. Bridging that gap is a design problem worth solving.",sec:[{h:"Opportunity",items:["Swipe gestures can encode complex actions","AI triage on mobile could match desktop speed","The same activation journey should work across devices"]}]},{d:"Mar 10, 2026",t:"The AI Drafting Moment",tg:"Vision",b:"I tried every AI email drafting tool I could find this week. Most feel like autocomplete on steroids. What makes Superhuman's approach different is context. When AI knows your writing style, your relationships, your priorities, drafting becomes collaboration rather than generation.",sec:[{h:"What Stands Out",items:["Context-aware AI feels like a thought partner","The best AI drafts need one edit, not a rewrite","Trust in AI grows with transparency in reasoning"]}]},{d:"Mar 5, 2026",t:"Split Inbox as Architecture",tg:"Design",b:"Split Inbox is one of those features that seems simple but reveals deep product thinking. By separating VIP, Team, Newsletters, and Notifications, Superhuman turns a firehose into four manageable streams. This is information architecture applied to the most personal data space we have.",sec:[{h:"Design Insight",items:["Categorization reduces cognitive load more than filtering","The default splits are opinionated and that is good","Each split can have its own triage rhythm"]}]},{d:"Feb 26, 2026",t:"Keyboard Shortcuts and Expertise",tg:"Research",b:"There is research showing that expert users of keyboard-driven tools report higher satisfaction and lower cognitive load than mouse-driven users doing the same tasks. Superhuman bets heavily on this. The question for activation is: how do you get someone from zero shortcuts to twenty without it feeling like homework?",sec:[{h:"Activation Idea",items:["Introduce one shortcut per session, not ten in a tutorial","Practice with real emails, not fake ones","Celebrate the speed gain immediately"]}]},{d:"Feb 18, 2026",t:"The Team Activation Problem",tg:"Industry",b:"Rolling out premium email to a team of 50 is not 50 individual activations. It is a social system. When Sarah uses shortcuts and Mike does not, the team moves at Mike's speed. Admin visibility into activation health is not a nice-to-have. It is essential for enterprise success.",sec:[{h:"Enterprise Insight",items:["Team activation requires social proof and peer learning","Admins need coaching tools, not just dashboards","The slowest adopter sets the team's ceiling"]}]},{d:"Feb 10, 2026",t:"What Notion Taught Me About Onboarding",tg:"Research",b:"Notion's onboarding has evolved dramatically over the years. Early versions dropped you into a blank page. Current versions use templates and guided workflows. The lesson: even power tools need guardrails for the first hour. Superhuman's synthetic inbox approach is the email equivalent.",sec:[{h:"Comparison",items:["Blank canvas is freedom for experts, paralysis for beginners","Templates and examples reduce time-to-first-value","The best onboarding teaches by doing, not telling"]}]},{d:"Feb 3, 2026",t:"Accessibility in Speed-First Design",tg:"Design",b:"Speed-first design creates tension with accessibility. Keyboard shortcuts assume motor precision. Dense information layouts assume visual acuity. I believe great product design finds ways to be fast AND accessible. These are not competing goals if you design for them together from the start.",sec:[{h:"Principles",items:["Every shortcut should have a discoverable alternative","Information density should be adjustable, not fixed","Speed gains should be measurable for every user, not just power users"]}]},{d:"Jan 28, 2026",t:"The Follow-Up Economy",tg:"Vision",b:"I have been tracking my own email behavior and discovered something: about 40 percent of my important emails are follow-ups on previous threads. Superhuman's reminder system addresses this, but there is an opportunity to make follow-through feel automatic rather than manual. An AI that tracks commitments across threads could be transformative.",sec:[{h:"Product Idea",items:["Automatic commitment extraction from email threads","Proactive reminders based on promised timelines","A follow-through score that builds accountability"]}]},{d:"Jan 20, 2026",t:"Why I Love Speculative Design",tg:"Process",b:"Speculative design lets you explore what could be without the constraints of what is. Building HyperFlow is not about telling Superhuman what to do. It is about showing how I think, how I research, how I translate insight into interaction. The artifact is the conversation starter. The thinking is the portfolio.",sec:[{h:"Philosophy",items:["Speculative design is thinking made visible","The process reveals the designer more than the output","Constraints come later. Curiosity comes first"]}]},{d:"Jan 14, 2026",t:"Superhuman's Design Language",tg:"Research",b:"I spent hours studying Superhuman's visual language. The restraint is remarkable. Two border radii (8px and 16px). Non-standard font weights like 460 and 540. A cream-and-charcoal palette that feels warm without being casual. Every choice is deliberate. This is what craft looks like in software.",sec:[{h:"Design Observations",items:["Binary radius system creates consistency without monotony","Custom font weights add subtle hierarchy","The color palette conveys premium without darkness"]}]},{d:"Jan 10, 2026",t:"The Activation Gap",tg:"Industry",b:"I have been deep-diving into the email productivity landscape and one pattern keeps emerging: the gap between powerful features and actual usage. Tools like Superhuman, Shortwave, and Spark all have impressive capabilities. But the difference between having a feature and having a user who relies on it daily is enormous. That gap is the activation gap, and it is where design has the most leverage.",sec:[{h:"Market Context",items:["Feature richness does not equal feature adoption","The first 7 days predict long-term retention","Design for the activation gap is an underinvested discipline"]}]}];
